    descriptionEN:
      "Located in Red Square in Moscow, near the Kremlin, it is distinguished by its brightly colored onion-shaped domes. This cathedral is often confused with the Cathedral of the Savior on Blood in Saint Petersburg. It is the most famous building in Russia and an international symbol of the city of Moscow. It was named after the Russian people and the Tsar who loved Saint Basil. The cathedral was commissioned by Ivan IV, known as Ivan the Terrible, to the architect Postnik Yaklov in Moscow to commemorate the fall of the Khanate of Kazan and continued from 1555 to 1561. The cathedral is located on the southeastern side of Red Square opposite the Spassky Tower of the Kremlin. The cathedral building is not large, as it contains nine temples built on a single foundation. The interior of the cathedral is a group of separate temples, each filled with icons, walls painted in medieval pink basalt colors, and various artworks on the inner walls of the domes.",
