    descriptionEN:
      "The Peter and Paul Fortress is the main fortress of the city of Saint Petersburg in Russia. It was founded by Peter the Great in 1703 according to designs by Domenico Trezzini as a fortress for the city. In the early 1920s, the Bolshevik government used it as a prison and place of execution. This large defensive fortress is located on Zayachy Island, and includes a cathedral, a former prison, and various exhibitions. It is the nucleus from which St. Petersburg grew into the current city. History buffs will love it, and everyone will see amazing panoramic views from the top of its walls. Currently, the place has been converted into a historical museum. By wandering around, you can discover many secrets and things about the city of St. Petersburg. The exterior part of the museum also contains beautiful gardens, by visiting which one can relax and unwind away from the hustle and bustle of life, in addition to the presence of a group of stone corridors and unique architectural buildings that are located in Surrounding the castle, the most famous of which is: the Peter and Paul Cathedral dating back to the eighteenth century AD.",
